references: Table¬†IV reports the accuracy of our proposed Question-Query mapping (QQmaping) approach in Sec IV-B. The mapping model is trained on the FVQA training splits and tested on the respective testing splits. To train the model, we use the Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD) with 100100100 Question-Query pairs as a mini-batch. Both the word embedding size and the LSTM memory cell size are 128128128. The learning rate is set to 0.0010.0010.001 and clip gradient is 101010. The dropout rate is set to 0.50.50.5. It converged after 505050 epochs of training. We also provide the results for different KB Sources of supporting facts. Questions asked based on facts from WebChild are much easier to be mapped than questions based on other two KBs. This is mainly because facts in WebChild are related to the ‚Äòcomparative‚Äô relationship, such as ‚Äòcar is faster than bike‚Äô, which further lead to user-generated questions are more repeated in similar formats. Table V shows the overall accuracy of all the baseline methods and our proposed models. In the case of Top-111 accuracy, our ‚Äòtop-3-QQmaping‚Äô is the best-performing single model, which doubles the accuracy of the baseline ‚ÄòLSTM-Question+Image‚Äô. Our proposed model also outperforms ‚ÄòLSTM-Question+Image+Pre-VQA‚Äô and ‚ÄòHie-Question+Image+Pre-VQA‚Äô, although the latter use additional training data. The ‚ÄòEnsemble‚Äô model achieves the best accuracy of 58.76%percent58.7658.76\%, showing that the conventional LSTM-based model and our knowledge based model are complementary. The ‚Äòtop-3-QQmaping model‚Äô outperforms ‚Äòtop-1-QQmaping‚Äô because it produces better Question-Query mapping results, as shown in the Table IV. However, it is still not as good as ‚Äògt-QQmaping‚Äô due to Question-Query mapping errors. There is still a significant gap between our models and the human performance. Among the baseline models, LSTM methods perform slightly better than SVM. ‚ÄòQuestion+Image‚Äô models always predict more accurate answers than ‚ÄòQuestion‚Äô or ‚ÄòImage‚Äô alone, no matter in SVM or LSTM. Interestingly, contradictory with previous works [9, 5] which found that ‚Äòquestion‚Äô plays a more important role than ‚Äòimage‚Äô in the VQA [5] or COCO-QA datasets¬†[9], our ‚Äò{SVM,LSTM}-Q‚Äô performs worse than ‚Äò{SVM,LSTM}-I‚Äô, meaning that FVQA questions rely more heavily on the image content than the existing VQA datasets. Actually, if ‚Äò{SVM,LSTM}-Q‚Äô achieves too high performance, the corresponding questions may be not Visual Questions and they may be actually Textual Questions.  The LSTM models that are pretrained on the VQA dataset performs slightly better than training from scratch, but not as well as our models. Using the Top-333 measure, our ‚Äòtop-3-QQmaping‚Äô model also performs best. We produce slightly lower Top-101010 performance, because our proposed methods may produce less than 101010 answers in some cases.

Table¬†IX illustrates the performance on questions that focus on different types of visual concepts, which are object, scene and action.
The performance on object-related questions is significantly higher than the other two types, especially when image features are given.

The accuracy of action or scene related questions is poorer than object-related questions (even for human subjects),

For example, the answer to ‚ÄòWhat can I do in this place‚Äô (the image scene is kitchen) can be ‚Äòpreparing food‚Äô or ‚Äòcooking‚Äô.
On the other hand, the performance of action classification is also worse than objects, which also leads to poor VQA performance.
